2 Prerequisites

We will need:

  • R
  • RStudio (integrated development environment for R, IDE):
    • cmd/ctrl-Enter to execute code and move to the next statement
    • cmd/ctrl-Shift-S to run the whole script
  • tidyverse package; packages/libraries are a collection of functions, data, and documentation that extend the capabilities of base R
  • other packages: library(nycflights13), library(plm), library(kableExtra), library(maps), library(ggalluvial), library(alluvial). We also use library(fs) but not that important

There are many different approaches/systems to read data, tidy data, plotting data,… in R. We focus on one approach based on the tidyverse packages. The notes are based on the book R for data science

The packages in the tidyverse share a common philosophy of data and R programming; they are designed to work together naturally. You install and load the tidyverse packages as follows:

install.packages("tidyverse") #install the package; has to be done only once
library(tidyverse) #has to be done each time you start a new R Session

3.1 Tibbles

Tibbles/data.frames and data.table (we won’t cover data.table here) are the most common way to store and work with data in R.

  • We are going to use tibbles (tbl_df) instead of R’s traditional data.frame
  • Tibbles are data frames but they tweak some older behavior

Example of a tibble/data.frame:

data("longley")
# View(longley) #or click on the data frame in your Environment View

Creating a tibble from vectors:

tibble(x = 1:5, y = 1, z = x ^2 + y) #recylce inputs of length 1

Subsetting:

# Extract a column by name
longley$GNP.deflator #selecting a column
longley[["GNP.deflator"]] #same thing as before

# Extract a column by position
longley[, 1] #all rows, first column

# Extract a row by positoin
longley[1, ] #first row, all columns

# First observations of GNP.deflator
longley$GNP.deflator[1]

# Second observation of second column
longley[2, 2]

Extract based on another variable:

var <- "Unemployed"
longley[, var]

3.2 Read Data: readr and readxl

  • We will read plain-text rectangular data and turn them into data.frames/tibbles
  • Common functions: read_csv(), read_csv2(), read_tsv(), read_delim(), read.xlsx()
  • readr vs base functions: readr is much faster, produces tibbles instead of data frames, don’t depend on your OS
  • We are assuming standard files are given (reading numeric values can be tricky because different countries use different representations). I am going to skip more advanced topics like string parsing and the locale argument which allows for
    • parsing columns which use, for example, , as decimal mark or . as grouping mark,
    • change encoding from UTF-8 to older formats (readr is assuming UTF-8 by default) \(\Rightarrow\) guess_encoding(),
    • correct parsing of dates (can be very tricky).

mobility_stats <- mobility_stats <- readr::read_csv(paste0(save_location, "mobility.csv"),

What happens here? readr guesses what kind of format the columns are based on the first 1000 entries. Columns sub_region_2 and census_fips_cod are NA for all countries but the US. But the US is at then end of the table. Therefore readr guesses all NA and makes the columns logical. At the end it receives characters and throws parsing failures.

Many different ways to deal with the problem. Probably the best solution is to investigate the data im more detail before reading it and provide more info for readr . I know that these two columns should be character columns. So we can use this knowledge: col_types = "ccccciDdddddd".

3.4 Data Transformation dplyr

This part should come after tidying data, but some functions discussed here are helpful for tidying data (therefore I am going to discuss this part first)

library(nycflights13) 
## Warning: package 'nycflights13' was built under R version 3.6.3
# library(tidyverse)

Have a look at flights data:

head(flights) #show first 10 rows of dataset
# View(flights) #complete dataset

Five key dplyr functions

  • filter() subset based on their values
  • arrange() reorder rows
  • select() pick variables by name
  • mutate() create new variables based on existing variables
  • summarize() collapse many values down to a single summary statistic

They can be used together with group_by() which changes the scope of each function - operation group-by-group.

They all work in a similar way:

  1. the first argument is a data frame
  2. subsequent arguments describe what to do with the data frame, using the variable names (without quotes)
  3. they result in a new data frame \(\Rightarrow\) no modification of existing data frame

3.4.1 filter()

alternative in base R: subset()

jan1_flights <- filter(flights, month == 1, day == 1)

Comparison Operators: >, >=, <=, <, !=, == Logical Operators: &, |, !

nov_dec_flights <- filter(flights, month == 11 | month == 12)

The %in% operator:

first_half_flights <- filter(flights, month %in% seq(1, 6))

3.4.2 NA (not available)

Computing statistics of incomplete data sets is strictly speaking not possible. Maybe the largest value occurred when you didn’t measure. Therefore, almost any operation involving an NA will result in NA

NA > 5
NA + 10
  • Determine if value is NA with is.na(x)
  • filter() excludes rows with NA
  • If you don’t mind the missing data and want to compute the statistics anyway, you can add the argument na.rm = TRUE (Should I remove the NAs? Yes!).

3.4.3 arrange()

  • Changes the order of rows; takes a data frame and set of columns to order by
  • use desc() to reorder by descending order
arrange(flights, year, month, day)
arrange(flights, desc(arr_delay))

3.4.4 select()

selecting variables (columns) and dropping others

select(flights, year, month, day)

Select all columns between year and day

select(flights, year:day)

Select all columns expect those from year to day

select(flights, -(year:day))
  • Select can also be used to rename, but see rename()
  • Using the everything() helper; useful if you want to move variables around
select(flights, time_hour, air_time, everything())

3.4.5 mutate()

Add new columns that are functions of existing columns

#refer to columns you just created
mutate(flights, 
       gain = arr_delay - dep_delay,
       hours = air_time / 60,
       gain_per_hour = gain / hours)

transmute to keep only variables which are created

3.4.6 summarize() and group_by()

  • Explain na.rm = TRUE later
summarize(flights, delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
  • It collapses a data frame to a single row
  • useful if paired with group_by(): this changes the unit of analysis from the complete dataset to individual groups
  • when you group by multiple variables, each summary peels off one level of the grouping
  • ungroup() to remove grouping
by_day <- group_by(flights, year, month)
by_day_summary <- summarize(by_day, count = n(),
                            mean_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE), 
                            sd_delay = sd(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
                            max_delay = max(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

3.5 Tidy Data: tidyr

  • We want the data to fit in a data.frame. A data.frame is a rectangular collection of variables (in the columns) and observations (in the rows) \(\Rightarrow\) tabular data

Data is tidy if:

  • each variable has its own column
  • each observation has its own row
  • each value has its own cell

tidy data

An example of tidy data:

head(pwt_v3)

Advantages of tidy data:

  • one consistent way \(\Rightarrow\) consistency of tools
  • vectorization of data manipulation becomes straight forward
  • most modeling tools expect tidy data and will throw errors otherwise

3.5.1 WEO data

head(ggdbt_weo)

The data is in wide format. Some of the column names are not variable names but values . Each row holds multiple observations, the values for the year 2006 until 2019.

We therefore have to gather those columns. We need three parameters:

  • The set of columns that represent values, not variables, i.e. the columns 2006 through 2019.
  • The name of the variable whose values form the column names. This will be “year” here. key
  • The name of the variables whose values are spread over the cells. This will be “gg_dbt” here value

We need the gather() command for this.

ggdbt_weo <- readxl::read_excel("C:/WBG/LocalITUtilities/R_tutorial/data/WEO projections.xlsx", na = c("n/a", "--"))
unique(ggdbt_weo$Scale) #I will have a look at some variables in the dataset first and delete them if we don't need them
unique(ggdbt_weo$`Subject Descriptor`) #another problem: bad variable names which reasults in backticks
unique(ggdbt_weo$Units)
unique(ggdbt_weo$`Country/Series-specific Notes`)

ggdbt_weo <- select(ggdbt_weo, -c(Scale, `Subject Descriptor`, Units, `Country/Series-specific Notes`, `2019 WEO`)) 
ggdbt_weo_long <- gather(ggdbt_weo, key = "Year", value = "GG_dbt", `2006`:`2019`, convert = TRUE) #convert  = TRUE tries to convert Year to integer (and manages to do so); otherwise character vector because they were characters before (column names))
ggdbt_weo_long <- arrange(ggdbt_weo_long, Code, Help, Year)

3.5.2 JHU Covid cases

covid_cases <- read_csv("W:/MFM/HighFreqMonitor/data/covid_cases.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   `Province/State` = col_character(),

covid_cases <- rename(covid_cases, State = `Province/State`, Country = `Country/Region`) #proper column names

covid_cases <- gather(covid_cases, key = "Date", value = "Cases", -c(State, Country)) #long format
covid_cases <- mutate(covid_cases, Date = parse_date(Date, format = "%m/%d/%y")) #advanced: make date columns (not necessary, but makes arrange work, next step)
covid_cases <- arrange(covid_cases, Country, State, Date) 
covid_cases <- select(covid_cases, Country, everything()) #rearrange columns, Country first, rest follows

3.5.3 Spreading

The opposite of gathering: long to wide.

Let’s assume we want to re-export the WEO data but we only want to keep 2019 data and we want wide format

ggdbt_weo_long <- filter(ggdbt_weo_long, Help == "2019 WEO")
ggdbt_weo_long <- select(ggdbt_weo_long, -Help)
ggdbt_weo_wide <- spread(ggdbt_weo_long, key = Year, value = GG_dbt)

3.6 Joining/Merging Tables

  • Linking multiple tables base on pair of tables
  • Tables are linked via variables,
    • the variables used to link tables are called keys
    • key are variable(s) which identify an observation
  • Primary key: identifies an observation in its own table
  • Foreign key: identifies an observation in another table

Let’s work with smaller versions of the WEO data and the PWT

pwt_small <- select(pwt, isocode, year, tcgdp) 
pwt_small <- filter(pwt_small, isocode %in% c("DJI", "DMA", "BWA")) #more countries, more years; but cut-off in 2010
ggdbt_small <- select(ggdbt_weo_long, isocode = Code, year = Year, GG_dbt) 
ggdbt_small <- filter(ggdbt_small, isocode %in% c("DJI", "DMA")) #rename variables to simplify join

Both tables have two columns to perform the join on: isocode, year. I renamed the variables in the second table to make the join simpler (not necessary but makes things simpler)

Different ways of joining/merging

dplyr package base package
inner_join(x, y) merge(x, y)
left_join(x, y) merge(x, y, all.x = TRUE)
right_join(x, y) merge(x, y, all.y = TRUE)
full_join(x, y) merge(x, y, all.x = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)

3.6.1 Inner Join/Merge

Inner Join

merged_table <- inner_join(pwt_small, ggdbt_small, by = c("isocode", "year")) #data is not scaled; should be done in next step

Outer Joins

merged_table2 <- left_join(pwt_small, ggdbt_small, by = c("isocode", "year")) #data is not scaled; should be done in next step
merged_table3 <- full_join(pwt_small, ggdbt_small, by = c("isocode", "year")) #data is not scaled; should be done in next step

3.6.2 Other joins

semi_join(x, y) keeps all observations in x that have a match in y

anti_join(x, y) drops all observations in x that have a match in y (useful for finding data which don’t match)

anti_join_table <- anti_join(pwt_small, ggdbt_small, by = c("isocode", "year")) #data is not scaled; should be done in next step

4 Visualization: Introduction to ggplot

These notes are based on “Data Visualization with ggplot2 Cheat Sheet”. Ggplot2 is based on the grammar of graphics, the idea that you can build every graph from the same few components: a data set, a set of geoms-visual marks that represent data points, and a coordinate system.

4.1 Function of ggplot

Before we start plotting we need to load the library and see the format of our data.

library(ggplot2)
mpg

4.3 Add Faceting and create a customized theme

We can also include facets that divide a plot into subplots based on the values of one or more discrete variables. Also we will change the theme (background coloring)to make our plots more appealing.

For more coloring options please refer to “R color cheatsheet”

# Introduce the customized theme 
my_theme <- theme_bw() + 
    theme(strip.background = 
    element_rect(fill="lightgoldenrod"), 
    legend.position="bottom",
    legend.title=element_blank(),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill="white",colour=NA) )

# Plot again using the new customized theme and faceting
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = cyl)) +
    geom_smooth(method ="lm") +
    facet_wrap(.~year)+
    coord_cartesian() +
    scale_color_gradient(low = "cyan", high = "black") +
    my_theme

# Fsacet into both rows and columns 
ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = cyl)) +
    geom_smooth(method ="lm") +
    facet_wrap(year~drv)+
    coord_cartesian() +
    scale_color_gradient(low = "cyan", high = "black") +
    my_theme

4.4 Position Adjustments

Position adjustments determine how to arrange geoms that would otherwise occupy the same space.

s <- ggplot(mpg, aes(fl, fill = drv))

# Arrange elements side by side 
s + geom_bar(position = "dodge")+
    my_theme

# Stack elements on top of one another, normalize height              
s + geom_bar(position = "fill")+
    my_theme

# Stack elements on top of one another 
s + geom_bar(position = "stack")+
    my_theme+
  scale_fill_brewer(palette="Set3")

dat$GC.DOD.TOTL.CN_<-dat$GC.DOD.TOTL.CN/dat$NY.GDP.MKTP.CD  # Total debt (central gov) debt
dat$GB.BAL.OVRL.GDP.ZS_<-(dat$GC.REV.XGRT.GD.ZS-dat$GC.XPN.TOTL.GD.ZS)/100 # Government budget balance (%GDP)
dat$BN.CAB.XOKA.GD.ZS_<-dat$BN.CAB.XOKA.GD.ZS/100  #Current account balance (%GDP)
colnames(dat)[3]<-"Year"
colnames(dat)[21]<-"Country"

Let’s assume our objective it to estimate the impact of debt on GDP growth:

\[\Delta ln(Y_t) = \alpha+\beta \frac{D_t}{Y_t P_t}+\varepsilon_t \] Let’s use our knowledge from Tibbles and create a dataframe with only these variables (in-class exercise):

dat<-dat %>% group_by(Country) %>% mutate(ly = log(NY.GDP.MKTP.KN),
                                          lylag = lag(ly, order_by=Country),
                                          dly = 100*(ly-lylag))  # Lag differences

5.3 Panel regression methods

Note that running pooled OLS will give us biased coefficients (apart from other problems such as endogeneity and causality, for which you need a structural model). We can get around the pooled assumption by either demeaning the data or using least square dummy variables.

For LSDV use:

fixed.dum <-lm(dly ~ GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_ + factor(Country) - 1, data=dd)
summary(fixed.dum)

We can do the standard test of whether fixed effects is better than OLS (H0: OLS is better than FE)

pFtest(fixedfin,reg1)
## 
##  F test for individual effects
## 
## data:  dly ~ GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_
## F = 3.5357, df1 = 175, df2 = 4329, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: significant effects

The results reject the null hypothesis - use fixed effects.

How about if we do a random effects model (when would we typically do this - think of between and within group variability)?

library(plm)
Randfin <-plm(dly ~ GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_,data=dd, index=c("Country","Year"),model="random")

Which model do we prefer - fixed or random effects? Luckily there is a test to help us - the Hausman test, although it comes with strong caveats. Use fixed effects if p-value < 0.05.

phtest(fixedfin,Randfin)
## 
##  Hausman Test
## 
## data:  dly ~ GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_
## chisq = 7.5749, df = 1, p-value = 0.005919
## alternative hypothesis: one model is inconsistent

Let’s plot the estimates for the three methods by adding the fitted values of the random and fixed effects model to the pooled estimate:

fitPLMFE <- pmodel.response(fixedfin)-fixedfin$residuals
fitPLMRE <- pmodel.response(Randfin)-Randfin$residuals
test$PanelFE <- fitPLMFE
test$PanelRE <- fitPLMRE

ggplot(data = test, aes(x = GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_, y = dly))+geom_point(color='blue')+
  geom_line(aes(y=.fitted, x=GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_,color='POOLED'))+
  geom_line(aes(y=PanelFE, x=GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_,color='FE'))+
  geom_line(aes(y=PanelRE, x=GG.DBT.TOTL.CN_,color='RE'))+
  labs(title="Simple relationship",x="Debt/y",y="GDP growth")+
  scale_color_manual(name="",breaks=c("POOLED","FE","RE"),values=c("RED","YELLOW","GREEN"))+
  theme_bw()

For other types of tests like unit roots, heteroscedasticity and serial correlation read: PLM Vignette
